<html><head><meta http-equiv="Content-Type" content="text/html; charset=utf-8" /><meta http-equiv="Content-Style-Type" content="text/css" /><meta name="generator" content="Aspose.Words for .NET 13.4.0.0" /><title>Written evidence from Institution of Civil Engineers’ (ICE) (LTD0038)</title></head><body><div><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:center"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:14pt; font-weight:bold">Written evidence from </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:14pt; font-weight:bold">Institution of Civil Engineers’ (ICE) (LTD0038)</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold; text-decoration:underline">Summary</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 10.52pt; padding-left:3.68pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">ICE </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">represents the independent expertise</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">of over 80,000 individual members. We regularly provide </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">advice to </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Government</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> on all aspects of planning, financing, building and operating infrastructure</span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 14.2pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 10.52pt; padding-left:3.68pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">We feel that it is too </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">soon</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> to make definitive judgements on the effectiveness </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">of the new local arrangements but </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">we have noted e</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">arly</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> concerns. We are </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">most </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">co</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">ncerned, however, at the overall constraints </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">on funding for local transport – somewhat in contrast to the situation for rail and </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">(</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">now also</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">)</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> strategic roads</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">. Our recent ‘State of the Nation’ sessions around England have repeatedly highlighted this divide be</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">tween the strategic and local networks</span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 10.52pt; padding-left:3.68pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Moves to simplify local transport expenditure, provide multi-year certainty and devolve decision-making powers away from Whitehall are welcome</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">. ICE is concerned, however, that the government’s latest arrangements are</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> not especially clear on the role of Local Transport Bodies</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> (LTBs)</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">. Theirs, and Local Enterprise Partnership</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> (LEP)</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">, geographic areas are also too small in some cases for a sufficiently strategic approach to transport planning and prioritisa</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">tion. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">It further</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> appears </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">that smaller LTBs, LEPs and their local authority partners may not always have sufficient expertise and capacity to make best use of the limited </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">and often diminishing </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">resources available</span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 10.52pt; padding-left:3.68pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">For larger urban areas, particularly city-regions, ICE fav</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">ours a transport </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">authority model similar to Transport for London</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> (TfL)</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">, with extensive powers across all modes and flexible</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">, certain</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> funding. Recent developments particularly Combined Authorities, are a positive </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">step</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> and should go further</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">. We recommended </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">such an approach in our ‘State of the Nation: Transport’ report earlier this year and will be developing our ideas in 2014</span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 10.52pt; padding-left:3.68pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Local </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">organisation</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">s should be encouraged to make more use of private and innovative sources of funding. In some places and for parti</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">cular types of project these can make a major contribution. But we are not convinced that they are sufficient to replace a large element of public funding in most cases. </span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold; text-decoration:underline">Introduction</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">(ICE</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> is a UK-based international organisation with </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">over</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> 80,000 members ranging from students to professional civil engineers. It is an educational and qualifying body and has charitable status under UK law. Founded in 1818, ICE has become recognised worldwide for its excellence as a centre of learning, as a qu</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">alifying body and as a public voice for the profession.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">ICE has access to a vast wealth of transport experience through its membership and draws on this to assist governments. This is delivered in many ways, including for example:</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:10pt; margin:4pt 0pt 0pt 9.6pt; padding-left:4.6pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Our flagship </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">‘</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">State of t</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">he Nation’</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> reports. This year’s focused on transport</span><a name="_ftnref1"></a><a href="#_ftn1">[1]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">, and was launched by Rt. Hon</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> Stephen Hammond in June. One of the report’s main recommendations was on devolution of transport</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> powers</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> and we will be developing this theme in 2014</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:10pt; margin:4pt 0pt 0pt 9.6pt; padding-left:4.6pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">ICE is a</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> core</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> partner i</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">n </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">the ‘Building a World Class Highways Supply Chain Initiative’, which works with Government to develop the skills and capabilities of the highways supply chain to achieve greater efficiency and value for money</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:10pt; margin:4pt 0pt 0pt 9.6pt; padding-left:4.6pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Our members are called on to provide advice </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">by senior civil servants and politicians, including to the Transport Select Committee.</span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">We have set out our responses to the Committee’s questions below and would be pleased to provide further insight at </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">subsequent</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> stages in the inquiry.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 14.29pt; padding-left:21.71pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">What is the ratio</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">nale for the Government’s proposals to devolve to a local level decision-making on transport expenditure? What are the advantages and disadvantages of the Government’s approach? Are there better models?</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">1.1.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">What is the </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">rationale?</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">1.1.1.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">We understand changes to </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">local transport expenditure to be part of Government’s delivery of its localism</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> agenda. This is particularly manifest in:</span></p><ul type="circle" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><ul type="circle" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Courier New'; font-size:12pt; margin:4pt 0pt 4pt 48.2pt; padding-left:2pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">abolition of the RDAs and their replacement with LEPs and LTBs</span></li><li style="font-family:'Courier New'; font-size:12pt; margin:4pt 0pt 0pt 48.2pt; padding-left:2pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">elements</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> of devolving power away from Whitehall towards local areas, particularly through City Deals and the Single Local Growth Fund (SLGF) – both of which are partly transport</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">focused</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> (including m</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">ajor </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">l</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">ocal </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">s</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">cheme</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">s)</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">.</span></li></ul></ul><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">1.2.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">What are the </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">advantages</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">? </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">1.2.1.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Devolution can </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">mean that transport expenditure decisions are made closer and more accountable to those local communities most affected by them. Local authorities are particularly accountable</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> -</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> although LEPs and LTBs, whilst local, are less directly accountable to local r</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">esidents</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">1.2.2.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Local organisations should better-understand the needs of their areas, and be better-able to identify and promote transport investment in pursuit of local ends </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">than a national transport department can. In particular, local organisations should b</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">e able to deploy</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> transport investment in pursuit of wider social, economic and environmental goals</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> – transport is a means to an end, after all</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">1.2.3.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">The reduction in the number of separate funding pots and streams for local transport is to be welcomed, as are </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">multi-year funding settlements. These should provide local bodies with more flexibility and certainty as a basis on which to plan to meet local needs and opportunities – instead of responding to central government’s often-changing priorities and criteria</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">1.2.4.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Reducing central government’s role may lead to investments being identified, appraised, approved and delivered more quickly.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">1.3.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">What are the </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">disadvantages</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">? </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">1.3.1.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">ICE has long called for a comprehensive national transport strategy for England. The </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">current l</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">ack of national </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">(and now also</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> regional</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">)</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> strategy means that decisions and schemes may exist without much regard for broader context, and the total of local schemes may not </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">sum to a commensurate contribution to broader goals (e.g. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">national connectivity</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">emi</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">ssions reduction</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">)</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">1.3.2.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Local area boundaries (whether local authority, LEP or LTB) can be quite small and organisations not well-equipped to understand or deal with some important travel patterns and corridors which have a larger-than-local focus. It may also</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> be that the optimum transport interventions may actually be outside the local area(s) which stand to benefit most, or span more than one area – a very local approach may be less well-suited to dealing with these</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">1.3.3.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">In six of England’s largest metropolitan </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">areas (outside London)</span><a name="_ftnref2"></a><a href="#_ftn2">[2]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> Integrated Transport Authorities </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">(ITAs) </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">(supported by Passenger Transport Executives</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> (PTEs)</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">) exist to address public transport issues across boundaries. While the boundaries of LEPs and LTBs are </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">coterminous with some of these</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">, it is</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> not the case in all and there may be scope for confusion and conflict between bodies with overlapping powers, boundaries and objectives</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> More generally, the overlapping boundaries of many LEPs (LTB boundaries do not overlap) may give rise to added confusi</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">on</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">1.3.4.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">The skills and resources available to smaller local bodies are sometimes limited, meaning that specialist knowledge and economies of scale may not be available. In addition, preparation of local major transport schemes requires considerable input of ti</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">me and effort. In competitive bidding situations (as opposed to the situation with formulaic allocations) considerable resources may be expended for no reward.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">1.3.5.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">It may be difficult for national transport bodies (such as the Highways Agency and Network </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Rail) to engage effectively with a large number of disparate and competing interests</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">It is unclear how that the funding periods for local transport allocations will align with those of Network Rail and the reformed Highways Agency – this may hinder co-ord</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">ination</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> of activity for maximum effect.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">1.3.6.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">The relatively modest funding available means that each transport body will only be able to promote </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">one or two</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> medium-sized projects in each funding period. CENTRO, the West Midlands PTE, estimate that a £20 million</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> scheme is now the largest which could be funded through their major scheme allocations for 2015-19.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">1.4.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Are there </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">better models</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">?</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">1.4.1.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">ICE believes it is not yet possible to assess the effectiveness of the new arrangements yet – they have not had enough time to </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">mature</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">1.4.2.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">We do not believe that there is an optimum ‘one size fits all’ model but for larger metropolitan areas, ICE favours </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">an </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">approach similar to </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">TfL. This offers a</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> comprehensive, integrated </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">organisation </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">with assured funding and </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">– experience in London su</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">ggests – can be </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">particularly effective where there are multiple modes and choices and less reliance on private cars</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">1.4.3.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Combined Authorities (CAs) are a step in the right direction, particularly in linking transport with land use and economic development pla</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">nning but may not be appropriate for all </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">locations and still lack some of the important powers and accountability of the London model</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">1.4.4.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">The pooling of large amounts of transport funding in the SLGF (into which LEPs bid) makes the potential contribution of </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">LTBs less clear.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">1.4.5.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">In all discussions of changes to funding criteria and streams, the total sum of funds available for local transport must be taken into account. Expenditure available for local transport, particularly capital, has been greatly reduced.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">1.4.6.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Also important when considering the merits of changing from one model to another are the costs associated with institutional and policy change. The disruption, uncertainty and delay incurred as a result of (all) governments</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">’</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> re-organisation</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">s</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> can be conside</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">rable – this argument</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">, and the benefits of stability and certainty,</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> seems to have been long-accepted in rail policy,</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> and</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> now also for the Strategic Road Network – but not </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">yet </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">for </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">local transport.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="2" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 14.29pt; padding-left:21.71pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Do local bodies (including local authorities, local enterp</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">rise partnerships, passenger transport executives, integrated transport authorities and local transport boards) have the capacity to assess, prioritise and deliver local transport schemes? What would the optimum delivery body look like?</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">2.1.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Capacity</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> to assess</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">, prioritise and deliver</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">2.1.1.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">ICE’s experience is that capacity levels are v</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">ery</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">, and perhaps increasingly,</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> variable</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">. L</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">arger local authorities </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">(particularly counties and larger unitaries) </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">and </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">ITAs/</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">PTEs</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> will generally have sufficient skilled staff for most transport-related tasks – although this is increasingly uncertain</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> as local funding is squeezed</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">2.1.2.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">S</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">maller local authorities </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">are less to have sufficient capacity. ICE’s consultations around the country (</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">as part of our ‘State of the Nation’ project) suggests that pressure on local authority budgets leading to headcount reductions threatens the capacity of smaller authorities to manage transport projects and programmes</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">2.1.3.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">The capacity of </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">LEPs </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">and</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> LTBs </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">is </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">heavily influenced by their local authority and ITA/PTE partners. Few of the new bodies employ transport specialists, or have delivery responsibility or capability themselves.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">2.2.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">What would the </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">optimum delivery body</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> look like?</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">2.2.1.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">As noted, we do not believe </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">there is a</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> single best model but </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">the TfL </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">integrated model </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">is </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">well-suited to larger urban areas with multiple modes. Combined Authorities go some way towards this model but still fall short</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">, lacking such clear democratic oversight and control over some </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">impo</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">rtant subjects</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">2.2.2.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Very local bodies </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">are </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">unlikely to have the strategic view or depth and breadth of skills required – an ideal model is likely to be “larger-than-local” at least</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">2.2.3.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">We consider that - in view of the diverse nature of the England’s local </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">geographies - it may be</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> more useful to think in terms of an optimum skillset </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">and range of attributes </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">rather than </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">a single model</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">. It is our experience, for example, that skills </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">in programme management</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> are in short supply across a range of organisation types</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="3" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 14.29pt; padding-left:21.71pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">What is the best way of dealing with major transport schemes that cross local authority boundaries or have wider regional impact?</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">3.1.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Major transport schemes can often</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> span local authority</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> boundaries and the wider sub-region, at least, needs to be considered.  Even this can be too small scale – cross-region issues frequently arise in the Midlands, </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">for example</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">3.2.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Ensuring co-operation among bodies can be difficult. The temptation to parochialism </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">may be strong and some areas - and perhaps particularly their </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">LEPs </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">- </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">may see themselves as being in competition</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> (indeed the Growth Fund encourages this)</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">. It shouldn’t be a </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">‘zero sum game’ but it is a considerable risk</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> that it will be seen as such</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">3.3.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">A mechanism akin to the </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">‘Duty to Co-operate’</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> which compels local planning authorities to work with their neighbours may be worth considering for </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">transport organisation</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">s. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Alternatively, some kind of regional process could also work, although any ‘top down’ or regional structure is unlikely to find favour with the current government.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">3.4.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">As previously noted, the ITA/PTE and TfL models exist to deal with schemes across metropoli</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">tan borough boundaries</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> – a sensible approach in our view.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="4" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 14.29pt; padding-left:21.71pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">How effectively do local bodies work with each other and with Government departments and national transport agencies?</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">4.1.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">The feedback we have received suggests a mixed picture, reflecting the varied</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> maturity of local arrangements, the diverse nature of the areas, and - invariably - the personalities involved.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">4.2.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">We are aware of some tensions between local organisations and national ones - the Highways Agency and Network Rail. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">T</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">his may be inevitable</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> to </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">some extent</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> as there are often likely to be more local demands than can be met by national agencies. Loss of the regional tier of governance has removed one level of mediation </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">and sifting of bids </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">between local and national organisations (although there cou</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">ld be friction between local and regional too, of course).</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">4.3.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Reform of the Highways Agency provides two important relevant opportunities in this context:</span></p><ul type="circle" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><ul type="circle" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Courier New'; font-size:12pt; margin:7pt 0pt 0pt 48.2pt; padding-left:2pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">firstly by providing the Agency with greater funding certainty, so that local areas can </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">better-understand, inform and respond to the Agency’s plans</span></li><li style="font-family:'Courier New'; font-size:12pt; margin:7pt 0pt 0pt 48.2pt; padding-left:2pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">secondly, and ideally informing the first, a clearer and better-understood set of objectives for the Agency, including direction on how it should involve local authorities, LEPs and LTBs. For tran</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">sport users, local and strategic networks should form a seamless whole – but this is often not the case, and the organisations responsible for different networks do not always have complementary objectives or incentives. ICE will be setting </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">out its views o</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">n this question in its response to the consultation on the reorganisation of the Highways Agency (closing 20 December 2013)</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">.</span></li></ul></ul><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">4.4.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Local authorities often feel that the relationship with the Department for Transport is unnecessarily top-down and micro-managed. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Recent changes may see a reduction day-to-day micro-management (such as competitive funding bids requiring very rapid</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> responses) but will also see a confusing</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> superstructure of LEPs and LTBs centrally-imposed.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="5" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 14.29pt; padding-left:21.71pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Do the current funding streams for major </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">local transport schemes meet the needs of local authorities? How do current funding streams compare with previous arrangements?</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">5.1.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">We have major concerns that the reduced scale of funds available for all local transport is insufficient. In our recent engagem</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">ent around England as part of our 2014 ‘State of the Nation’ development process, the level and certainty of future funding for local transport (roads and public transport, capital and revenue) has repeatedly featured as one of the greatest concerns across</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> all infrastructure issues</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">5.2.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">We welcome the intention to simplify funding streams, and reduce the </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">number of separate competitions.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">5.3.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">ICE broadly welcomed decision</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">s</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> in recent years to replace the competitive bidding process for “Integrated Transport and Main</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">tenance” with – firstly, in December 2010 – an indicative allocation, and then – in September 2012 – the decision to devolve the decision-making process for local major transport schemes. ICE believes that decisions should be made close to those most affec</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">ted by them. We also believe that competitive bidding does not always lead to the desired outcomes (it can favours those best at bidding, rather than the greatest need, and may militate against balanced programmes of expenditure (including maintenance))</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">5.4.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">The more recent decision to allocate large amounts of funding to the SLGF causes us concerns over whether transport needs will be adequately resource</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">d</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">, and causes us (and others) some confusion as to the future role of the LTBs</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">5.5.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">We are unclear how </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">effectively the proposed allocation schedules will fit with Network Rail’s and the Highways Agency’s current and proposed funding and programming arrangements</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">5.6.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Taking a broad view of local transport expenditure, we are concerned that the ring-fencing of </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">concessionary fares budgets may be distorting local public transport support spending.  ADEPT recently reported</span><a name="_ftnref3"></a><a href="#_ftn3">[3]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> that councils are spending 65%-75% of their public transport budgets on concessionary fares.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="6" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 14.29pt; padding-left:21.71pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">What impact will the devolution in 2015 of fundi</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">ng to Local Transport Bodies and the introduction of the Single Local Growth Fund have?</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">6.1.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">ICE believes that </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">it makes sense for transport issues to be considered alongside the many other issues that impact on economic growth in local areas, and </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">for </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">funding t</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">o be prioritised accordingly</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">. However, as with other questions, it is </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">too early to say </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">with certainty how the new arrangements will work in practice.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">6.2.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">It is </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">essential that the full impact of transport investment or disinvestment on economic growth is </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">properly considered when local decisions are being taken</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">. This requires that </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">partnerships must have access to the appropriate skills and knowledge, and it isn’t clear whether this will be the case</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> with regard to transport investment.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">6.3.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">A 44% top slicing of </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Integrated Transport Block funding into the </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">SGLF</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> seems disproportionate relative to other contribution sources.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">6.4.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">From our engagement with members and partner organisations, there seems to be widespread uncertainty as to the future role of the LTBs.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="7" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 14.29pt; padding-left:21.71pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">How c</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">an local authorities attract greater investment from the private sector for the delivery and maintenance of local transport infrastructure? What scope is there for the use of alternative funding streams?</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 39.6pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">7.1.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Local transport has traditionally relied heavily on</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> straightforward public sector grant funding. With the reduction in such resources available for local transport (in contrast to rail and the Strategic Road Network), local organisations have much incentive to seek alternative sources</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">7.2.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Some alternative so</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">urces are well-established; others are only emerging, or have yet to be adopted. It is unclear to us that alternative sources could compensate for reductions in public funding in the short-medium term – although they will be important for specific purposes</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> and in specific locations</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">7.3.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Local planning authorities have long been able to secure developer contributions for infrastructure improvements through Section 106 of the Planning Act (and its predecessors). Such contributions are a well-established principl</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">e but only available in specific circumstances. Recent tightening of the criteria, their application and the ability and willingness of developers to contribute in a difficult economic climate mean that Section 106 is unlikely to assume much greater import</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">ance in future.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">7.4.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Also planning-related, the Community Infrastructure Levy (CIL) offers opportunities to use developer contributions more flexibly than Section 106. Introduction of CIL (as with Section 106) appears to favour economically stronger locations </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">where there is more development interest and value</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">7.5.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Crossrail</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> is an excellent example of how private funding can be secured for transport investment – it uses CIL, business rate supplements and other developer contributions to provide a large share of the project’s funds. It is unlikely that many projects not servin</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">g high-value locations in London could put together such a package, however</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">7.6.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Government has, and seeks to continue to, broaden the uses to which CIL might be put. For example, the new National Infrastructure Plan suggests that CIL might be used to fund </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">di</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">rect compensation to individuals affected by development. While this may be a worthwhile use, it does dilute CIL’s original purpose</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> by reducing the sums available for new infrastructure</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">. The ICE warned in 2011, during the passage of the Localism Bill, that</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> CIL might simply become a tax on development – this appears to be coming to pass</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">7.7.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">City Deals have included a number of mechanisms for securing private sector funding for local infrastructure investment. Greater Manchester’s ‘Earn Back’ scheme is of parti</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">cular interest, allowing the area to capture the increases in tax contributions generated by infrastructure investment</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">7.8.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Tax Increment Financing (TIF) models, which have some similarities with ‘Earn Back’ are being investigated for use in England. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">In the U</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">K, </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Scotland has pioneered this approach, although not without some difficulty</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">7.9.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Some areas, notably West Yorkshire, have pursued infrastructure funds using small Council Tax levies or combinations of other incomes (such as CIL or S106) to lever additional </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">private finance. However, this source may be at risk with recent announcements from the Department for Communities and Loca</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">l Government on limits to annual</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> increases in local taxation.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">7.10.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">A clear income stream is important to attract private sector investors</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">. This may be more difficult to demonstrate in local transport – typically roads – than is the case for most utilities. Attempts to introduce road user charging or tolls (such as in Manchester and Edinburgh) have failed. Workplace parking levies have been </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">introduced in Nottingham but Bristol shelved plans for its own scheme</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">7.11.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">The above examples are merely a selection. It is clear that there are an increasing number of alternative funding options open to local authorities. These are valuable and should be pu</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">rsued but it remains unclear how widely applicable they are, and the extent to which they can compensate for reductions in mainstream public funding.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="8" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 14.29pt; padding-left:21.71pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">How clear are the lines of accountability for local decision making on transport expenditure?</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">8.1.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Accountability is becoming less clear. With the abolition of the RDAs, local authorities were generally responsible for local transport – notwithstanding that they have modest influence over the rail network or commercial (de-regulated) bus services. Large</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> metropolitan areas dealt with public transport issues through ITAs/PTEs, although local roads remained the concern of individual councils</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">8.2.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">The introduction of CAs, while welcome from a strategic policy perspective, has given rise to some uncertainties ab</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">out accountability – these might already have existed around ITAs/PTEs to some extent but the broader focus of the CAs widens this question</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">8.3.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">The introduction of LEPs, in particular, gives rise to uncertainty about local accountability. It is likely that </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">some will establish clearer and more accountable procedures than others.</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">December 2013</span><a name="_GoBack"></a></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p></div><hr style="width:33%; height:1px; text-align:left" /><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn1"></a><a href="#_ftnref1">[1]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> </span><a href="http://www.ice.org.uk/stateofthenation"><span style="color:#0000ff; font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; text-decoration:underline">www.ice.org.uk/stateofthenation</span></a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn2"></a><a href="#_ftnref2">[2]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10.5pt"> Greater Manchester; Merseyside; South Yorkshire; Tyne and Wear; West Midlands; and West Yorkshire</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn3"></a><a href="#_ftnref3">[3]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> ADEPT (2013) </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">Prospectus for Growth</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> (</span><a href="http://www.adeptnet.org.uk/prospectus.php"><span style="color:#0000ff; font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; text-decoration:underline">www.adeptnet.org.uk/prospectus.php</span></a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">) </span></p></body></html>